# Coding Best Practices

Applies to all languages. Language-specific conventions live in their own rules.

## Formatting

- Indentation: 2 spaces per level (or 1 tab rendered as 2 spaces).
- Keep lines reasonably short; wrap long expressions for readability.
- Use the project's formatter/linter; do not hand-format against it.

## Core Principles

### DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself
Extract shared logic into functions, classes, or modules. If you copy-paste code, refactor it.

### KISS — Keep It Simple, Stupid
Choose the simplest solution that works. Avoid clever tricks, unnecessary abstractions, and premature generalization.

### YAGNI — You Aren't Gonna Need It
Don't build features, abstractions, or flexibility "just in case." Add complexity only when there is a concrete requirement.

### Single Responsibility
Every function, class, and module should do one thing well. If a description needs "and," it's doing too much.

### Separation of Concerns
Keep business logic, I/O, presentation, and configuration in distinct layers. Don't mix HTTP handling with database queries.

### Least Surprise
Code should behave the way a reader would expect. Prefer conventional names, standard patterns, and predictable control flow.

## Clean Code Standards

### Naming
- Names should reveal intent: `remainingRetries` not `r`, `isValid` not `flag`.
- Functions: verb phrases (`fetchUser`, `validateInput`).
- Booleans: question form (`isReady`, `hasAccess`, `shouldRetry`).
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood (`id`, `url`, `http`).
- Follow the casing convention of the language (camelCase, snake_case, PascalCase).

### Functions
- Small and focused — ideally under 20 lines.
- Minimal parameters (3 or fewer). Group related params into a data object.
- One level of abstraction per function. Don't mix high-level orchestration with low-level details.
- No side effects unless the name clearly signals them.

### Constants & Magic Values
- No magic numbers or strings in business logic — extract to named constants.
- All constants live in a `constants/` folder, split into separate files by context (e.g. `constants/http.ts`, `constants/auth.ts`, `constants/limits.ts`).
- Import constants from their dedicated module; do not redeclare the same value in multiple places.

### Immutability
- Prefer immutable data and pure transformations over in-place mutation.
- Treat function arguments as read-only; return new values instead of mutating inputs.

### Error Handling
- Fail fast: validate inputs early, raise on invalid state.
- Catch specific exceptions, never bare/blanket catches.
- Always log or re-raise — never silently swallow errors.
- Use custom exception/error types for domain errors.

### Comments
- Don't comment *what* — the code should say that.
- Comment *why* — non-obvious intent, trade-offs, workarounds.
- Delete commented-out code. That's what version control is for.

### Dependencies
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces/protocols), not concrete implementations.
- Inject dependencies rather than hard-coding them.

## Boundary Validation

- Validate and normalize all external input (HTTP, env, files, user input) at the edges; trust the core.
- Reject invalid input with clear, actionable errors — don't coerce silently.
- Define a schema/type for every external boundary and derive internal types from it.

## Logging & Observability

- Use structured logs with context (request id, user id, operation name).
- Pick the right level: `debug` for diagnostics, `info` for lifecycle, `warn` for recoverable issues, `error` for failures.
- Never log personal data (PII) or any unclassified user input.
- Log once per error at the boundary that handles it; don't log-and-rethrow at every layer.

## Configuration & Secrets

- Read configuration from environment or a config layer; no hardcoded URLs, hosts, or feature flags.
- Secrets never live in source, logs, or error messages.
- Validate required config at startup and fail fast if missing or malformed.

## Security Basics

- Never `eval` or dynamically execute untrusted input.
- Always escape or parameterize before passing data to interpreters (SQL, shell, HTML, regex).
- Default-deny on authorization checks; require explicit allow.

## Code Organization

- Keep files focused and short. Split when a file exceeds ~300 lines when possible.
- Group by feature/domain, not by technical layer when possible.
- Public API at the top of the module, private helpers below.
- Imports at the top, sorted and grouped (stdlib → third-party → local).
